BUSINESS UNDERSTANDING¶

Background¶

The City of Dallas has a strong commmitment to transparency and accountability. Citizens or interested parties are provided an invaluable resource to easily access data published by the City. This data acts as a bridge between the citizens of Dallas and the city. It breakdowns barriers for information access by providing access to information where one can instantly review, compare, visualize, analyze and share. It is also a valuable resource for anyone wanting to move to the Dallas area or start a business with instant access to crime rates, hate crimes etc.

It allows the citizenry of Dallas to better understand how their city is performing. It also allows citizens to be better informed and to more effectively collaborate with policymakers and service providers. This helps make Dallas a more open, accessible, transparent and collaborative community.

The dataset is a valuable resource for citizens, business leaders and civic leaders seeking to improve governance, public services and the quality of life in Dallas.

It represents the Dallas Police Public Data - RMS Incidents from June 1, 2014 to September 7 2018. The information contained in this dataset allows Dallasites to access accurate information in a timely manner. Crime classifications are based on information supplied to the Dallas Police Department. This information is preliminary and could be reclassified later based on further investigation.

Crime classifications are based upon preliminary information supplied to the Dallas Police Department by the reporting parties and the preliminary classifications may be changed at a later date based upon additional investigation. The data set suppresses sexually oriented offenses, offenses where juveniles or children are the victim or suspect, property items that are considered evidence, Social Service Referral offenses, and identifying vehicle information in certain offenses for the sake of security.

To ensure that privacy concerns are protected, and legal standards are met, report data is "filtered" prior to being made available to the public. Among the exclusions are:

  • Sexually oriented offenses

  • Offenses where juveniles or children (individuals under 17 years of age) are the victim or suspect

  • Listing of property items that are considered evidence

  • Social Service Referral offenses

  • Identifying vehicle information in certain offenses

  • From June 1, 2014 to September 7, 2018

Business Objectives¶

Our analysis focused on classifying data into meaningful groups based on type of crimes, victims, arrests and associated response times. Furthermore, we wanted to examine the impact of population demographics by stratifying crimes based on age, sex and ethnicity. Another question of interest was the seasonality of crime cycles in the Dallas area and we conducted a time series analysis to better understand the seasonality.

We further used the Call received time, Call cleared time and Call dispatch time to compute the responding officer's response time. We further proceeded to identify a relationship between the response time and the incident location, incident type, incident time (morning, evening or night), witnesess involved or not etc. Person_Involvement_Type can be used to analysis if the response time fast if there is the witness involved int.

Another area of interest was to conduct a Time series analysis to identify crime patterns over time. We elected to analyze the data set to help us track response times for reported incidents in the Dallas region using different grouping factors.

  • Incidents by Division

  • Victim Profile Analysis by Race, Age, City of incident, Offense type

  • Correlation between Arrests made and Response time

  • Conversion rate of dispatches to arrests by priority of calls

  • Response times relative to Location and Population density

  • Crime incidents as a percentage of the population of that area to understand crime rates

  • Median dispatch times by division

  • Track crime, Classification time, Response time

  • Crime incidents by days of week, months and across years

  • Cross validation, Dividing the data set into test and train

Success Criteria¶

We should be able to accurately categorize and classify incidents, Response times and crime patterns and be able to predict likelihood of arrests. This will enable the police departments to better plan their resourcing and training needs as well as provide superior service levels to the community.

DATA QUALITY¶

Attribute Selection¶

From the original dataset above, we selected 35 variables for our analysis and eliminated 65 attributes in our analysis for the following reasons:

  • Redundant attributes were excluded as they can be parsed from attributes i.e. incident number, incident year and number of offenses can be derived from the service number field.

  • Irrelevant attributes such as address, apartment number etc. were excluded as they contributed little to our analysis.

  • Attributes with significant missing values were also omitted as they could not be used for our analysis i.e. Victim Package, Special Report (Pre-RMS), etc.

Let's review the datatypes of the selected attributes and the first 3 rows with headers

Removing whitespace and enforcing a consistent naming convention¶

We have trimmed the leading/trailing spaces in the columns names that we'd use for our analysis. We are also standardizing our data types by eliminating whitespace in attribute names and replacing spaces in column names with "underscores".

Missing value analysis and data cleansing¶

We did an analysis of the percentage of missing values in our dataset by attribute to understand the extent of the issue with the subset we selected. Given the large data set of 466K observations, we felt that the impact of some missing values in certain attributes would not significantly impact our analysis.

  • Explain missing data values
    • Hate_Crime: There are only 376 values in this attribute. However, this is an important field that local jurisdictions must feed to the FBI as it is a key national metric. The default value is "blank" or "no" which explains why only those incidents with are investigated and deemed as true Hate Crimes had an explicit value of "YES".
    • Victim_Age: By design the ages of juveniles and minors have been willfully eliminated from the dataset due to sensitivity reasons
    • Victim_Age_at_Offense:Missing values are for the same reason as listed above
    • Victim_Race:Missing values were tagged as Unknown
    • Victim_Gender:Missing values were tagged as Unknown
    • Victim_City:Missing values in this attribute were assigned a value of "DALLAS" given the dataset is primarily focused on the Dallas area

Data Standardization¶

DIVISION¶

  • Standardized by making all values upper caps for improved grouping
  • Reasons for mistakes in data
    • Some mistakes in the data were clearly attributable to typos by either officers or dispatchers but were easily cleaned up such as sector, year, division etc.
In [6]:
#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Converting Division attribute to upper case for standardization and aggregation
#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
incident.loc[:,'Division']=incident['Division'].str.upper()
incident.loc[:,'Division'].fillna('Unknown', inplace=True)

COUNCIL DISTRICT¶

  • Standardized to address data errors where the leading "D" was missing so values are aligned to the correct division

  • Deletion and imputation

    • We did not delete any data but excluded NULL values in some of the visualizations. Given most of the data in the set was categorical we chose not to impute data as we had a very large dataset of 466K observations.

VICTIM RACE (Ethnicity)¶

  • Victim_Race was aligned with the US Census Bureau standards on race and ethnicity as below. However, we did deviate from the US Census categories and retained Latino or Hispanic as a distinct ethnic group and did not merge it with American Indian or Alaska Native

    • White A person having origins in any of the original peoples of Europe, the Middle East, or North Africa.

    • Black or African American A person having origins in any of the Black racial groups of Africa.

    • American Indian or Alaska Native A person having origins in any of the original peoples of North and South America (including Central America) and who maintains tribal affiliation or community attachment.

    • Asian A person having origins in any of the original peoples of the Far East, Southeast Asia, or the Indian subcontinent including, for example, Cambodia, China, India, Japan, Korea, Malaysia, Pakistan, the Philippine Islands, Thailand, and Vietnam.

    • Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander A person having origins in any of the original peoples of Hawaii, Guam, Samoa, or other Pacific Islands.

    • Latino or Hispanic A person from Mexico or South and Central America

(Source: US Census Bureau)

NEW Calculated Columns added to the dataset¶

In order to better analyze the datset we decided to derive additional attributes as below.

In [15]:
#-----------------------------------------------------------------
# Coding Binary variables for some columns  
#-----------------------------------------------------------------
def get_binary_code(row):
    if row == 'Yes':
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

#-----------------------------------------------------------------    
# Arrest_status variable binary coding
#-----------------------------------------------------------------
def get_status(row):
    if row['Offense_Status']=='Clear by Arrest':
        return 1
    elif row['Offense_Status']=='Clear by Exceptional Arrest':
        return 1
    else:
        return 0

#-----------------------------------------------------------------
# Converting string to datetimes
#-----------------------------------------------------------------

incident.loc[:,'Call_Received']= pd.to_datetime(incident['Call_Received_Date_Time'], 
                                                format="%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")
incident.loc[:,'Call_Cleared']= pd.to_datetime(incident['Call_Cleared_Date_Time'], 
                                               format="%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")
incident.loc[:,'Call_Dispatch']= pd.to_datetime(incident['Call_Dispatch_Date_Time'], 
                                                format="%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p")

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Parsing number of offenses per incident from 'Service_Number_ID' data definition
#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
incident.loc[:,'Number_of_offense']= incident['Service_Number_ID'].str.split("-",
                                                                             expand=True).rename(columns = {2:'Number_of_offense'})


# incident.loc[:,'Year_of_offense']= incident['Service_Number_ID'].str.split("-",
#                                                                              expand=True).rename(columns = {1:'Year_of_offense'})

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Calculating response time from Call Received to Call Dispatch from original 
# columns 'Call_Received_Date_Time' and 'Call_Dispatch_Date_Time'
#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
incident.loc[:,'Response_time'] = pd.Series(data=(incident['Call_Dispatch']-incident['Call_Received']).astype('timedelta64[m]').astype('float'),
                                          index=incident.index,name='Response_Time')


#-----------------------------------------------------------------
# Parsing Latitude and Longitude values from 'Location1 attribute 
#-----------------------------------------------------------------
incident.loc[:,'Latitude']= incident['Location1'].str.split("\n",
                                                            expand=True)[2].str.split(',',
                                                                                      expand=True)[0].str.split('(',
                                                                                                                expand=True).rename(columns = {1 : 'Latitude'}).astype(int, errors='ignore')
                                                                                                  
incident.loc[:,'Longitude']= incident['Location1'].str.split("\n",
                                                            expand=True)[2].str.split(',',
                                                                                      expand=True)[1].str.split(')',
                                                                                                                expand=True).rename(columns = {0 : 'Longitude'}).astype(int, errors='ignore')

#------------------------------------------------------------
# Incident arrest status based on "Offense_Status" attribute
#------------------------------------------------------------
incident.loc[:,'Arrest_status']= incident.apply(get_status, axis=1) 

#--------------------------------------------
# Applying Binary Coding to these attributes
#--------------------------------------------
incident.loc[:,'Hate_Crime'] = incident['Hate_Crime'].apply(get_binary_code)
incident.loc[:,'Gang_Related_Offense'] = incident['Gang_Related_Offense'].apply(get_binary_code)
incident.loc[:,'Drug_Related'] = incident['Drug_Related'].apply(get_binary_code)
  • The following attributes were either parsed or calculated from other attributes
    • Number_of_Offense: Number of offenses per reported incident number
    • Response_Time: This is the time between receiving the call and dispatching it to officers for investigation
    • Call_Received: This is the time when the call was received by the 911 call center.
    • Call_Cleared: This is the time when the call was cleared at the 911 call center.
    • Call_Dispatch: This is the time when the call was dispatched by the 911 call center to the police officer.
    • Latitude: The latitude is parsed from the Location1 column.
    • Longitude: The longitude is parsed from the Location1 column.
    • Arrest_Status: This is binary but converted to integers Yes=1, No=0
  • Following attributes were Standardized to better visualize
    • Hate_Crime
    • Gang_Related_Offense
    • Drug_Related_Incident

#------------------------------------------------------
# Plot IQR for Response Time - 25th and 75th quartiles

q75, q25 = np.percentile(incident.Response_time.dropna(), [75 ,25])

#--------------------
# Calculate the IQR
#--------------------
iqr = q75 - q25

#-----------------------------------------------------
# Establish the limits for the outliers using the IQR

max = q75 + (iqr*1.5)

print('Maximum Outlier Threshold Value: ',max)

SIMPLE STATISTICS¶

The exploratory statistics on the Response_time calculated above proved to be more insightful since time and date alone were not adequate to answer the underlying questions of interest we had.

Per the Dallas Police Department, the trend of YTD average response times for priority 1 calls has decreased year over year from 2017 to 2018 YTD from 8.28 minutes to 8.13 minutes respectively.

(Source: https://www.dallaspolice.net/resources/CrimeReports/New%20Response%20Time%20Report.pdf)

Missing and non-standard data values detected while calculating response time appeared to be mainly due to recording errors. For the sake of this analysis incidents having response times greater than 24 hours have been ignored while performing simple statistical procedures.

The statistical summary of mean, std, min, max, IQR(25%, 50%, 75%) provided us with some more information on how to deal with these situations. The histogram plotted enabled us to get better understanding and visualization of the distributions.

Looks like Sector, Beat and reporting area is highly correlated with X_Coordinate, Y_Coordinate, Arrest_Status and Response Time. That make sense as per the police department org chart setup as below:

  • Division: Dallas Partrol divisions including Centrol, North Central, Northeast, Northwest, South Central, Southeast, Southwest, and Headquarters.

  • Sector is an approach to policing whereby the service area of a police station is divided into smaller, manageable areas known as sectors. For each sector, the SAPS appoint a police official who is known as the sector commander.

  • Beat is the territory and time that a police officer patrols.Beat policing is based on traditional policing (late 19th century) and utilises the close relationship with the community members within the assigned beat to strengthen police effectiveness and encourage cooperative efforts to make a safer community. Beat police typically patrol on foot or bicycle which provides more interaction between police and community members.

  • Reporting Area: Each Beat contains neighborhoods which are referred to as Reporting Areas.

  • Here is the detail about how Dallas city police department is divided by council district, division, sector, beat and Reporting Area http://www.dallaspolice.net/abouts/maps

We also observe the following correlations:

  • Watch or shift is highly correlated with Calls received by hour as we have observed previously in our prior visualization.

  • Arrest status is also correlated to response time which we have highlighted above, but will further analyze below so the impact of early response time to arrests is confirmed.

Exceptional Work¶

To complement our Police Incident dataset we imported the following datasets to provide greater insight for our analysis. This enabled us to better understand arrest rates against incidents as well as consider population factors that may play a critical role in effective policing of a large metropolitan city like DALLAS.

  • Police Arrests dataset
  • Population Density dataset

We also Geo-Mapped the data using Zip codes in Power BI to provide an enhanced visualization of crime pockets in the Dallas area.

Our research found that there are two categories of offenses reported in the NIBRS: Group A and Group B. It is important to determine which category an offense belongs to because the reporting requirements for Group A offenses and Group B offenses are different. Group A offenses are used to report all incidents committed within a law enforcement agencys jurisdiction to the NIBRS, whereas Group B offenses are used only to report arrest data. The following criteria were used to determine if a crime should be designated as a Group A offense:

  • The seriousness or significance of the offense.
  • The frequency or volume of its occurrence.
  • The prevalence of the offense nationwide.
  • The probability of the offense being brought to law enforcements attention.
  • The likelihood that law enforcement is the best channel for collecting data regarding the offense.
  • The burden placed on law enforcement to collect data on the offense.
  • The national statistical validity and usefulness of the collected data.
  • The FBI UCR Programs responsibility to make crime data available not only to law enforcement but to others having a legitimate interest in it.

There are 22 Group A offense categories making up 46 Group A offenses. Each offenses corresponding UCR Offense Code precedes its name. Immediately following the name of each offense name is an indication of whether it involves a Crime Against Person, Crime Against Property, or Crime Against Society.

There are 11 Group B offense categories. They encompass all of the crimes that are not Group A offenses.

(Source:FBI.gov) )
